# Seam Carving Algorithms in C++

Implementation and analysis of seam carving algorithms to find minimum-energy seams in images, using brute force, backtracking and dynamic programming approaches.

## Context
This project was developed as part of the course Tecnología Digital V: Diseño de Algoritmos (UTDT, 2026).

## Authors
- Luca Mateo Fernández Ciatti  
- Candela Sol González Lima  
- Germán Gómez Bonelli  

## My contribution
I contributed to the implementation of:
- Brute Force algorithm (C++)
- Backtracking algorithm (C++)
- Dynamic Programming algorithm (C++)
Additionally, I collaborated with my teammates on the experimental design and the writing of the report.

The rest of the codebase (image handling, utilities, etc.) was provided by the course.

## Description
The project focuses on solving the seam carving problem by modeling the image as an energy matrix and finding a minimum-energy path from top to bottom.

We implemented and compared three approaches:
- Brute Force (exponential complexity)
- Backtracking with pruning
- Dynamic Programming (optimal solution in O(n·m))

## Experiments
We conducted experiments comparing:
- Performance of C++ vs Python implementations  
- Execution time on grayscale vs color images  
- Impact of image structure on backtracking performance  

## Results
- Dynamic programming is significantly more efficient 
- Backtracking performance depends heavily on input structure and content, while dynamic programming doesn't  
- C++ consistently outperforms Python in execution time  

## Notes
This repository contains only the parts of the implementation developed by the authors. Some base files were provided by the course.
